First, we registered API key to access NHGIS data, then we defined an extraction of demographic data (CW8 table) at the county level for the year 2010. Next, we submitted the extraction, waited for it to complete, and downloaded the files to our local folder. Finally, we read the extracted files into R to analyze and visualize the data.

data_2010 <- CW8 %>%
  select(GISJOIN, STATE, STATEA, COUNTY, ends_with("2010"))
colnames(data_2010)

Now we select the relevant columns for the year 2010, then created new variables by combining male and female population counts by race (white, black, Native American, Asian, other, and mixed), and finally we removed the original CW8-coded columns to keep only the new aggregated population variables.

Here we filtered the dataset to keep only the records for Los Angeles County in 2010, then calculated the total population by summing the white, black, Native American, Asian, other, and mixed population groups.

# Prepare data
racial_data <- la_county_2010 %>%
  summarise(
    pop_white   = sum(pop_white, na.rm = TRUE),
    pop_black   = sum(pop_black, na.rm = TRUE),
    pop_native  = sum(pop_native, na.rm = TRUE),
    pop_asian   = sum(pop_asian, na.rm = TRUE),
    pop_other   = sum(pop_other, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = everything(), names_to = "race", values_to = "population") %>%
  mutate(
    race_label = recode(race,
                        pop_white = "White",
                        pop_black = "Black",
                        pop_native = "Native",
                        pop_asian = "Asian",
                        pop_other = "Other"),
    race_label = factor(race_label, levels = c("White", "Black", "Asian", "Native", "Other"))
  )
#colors for each categories
set2_colors <- c(
  "White" = "#FF69B4",
  "Black" = "#556B2F",
  "Asian" = "#66c2a5",
  "Native" = "#8da0cb",
  "Other" = "#e78ac3"
)

#First graph: internal labels except for Native, abscissa in scientific notation
plot1 <- ggplot(racial_data, aes(y = race_label, x = population, fill = race_label)) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_text(aes(label = race_label),
            hjust = ifelse(racial_data$race_label == "Native", -0.1, 1.1),
            color = "black",
            size = 5) +
  labs(
    title = "Country: Los Angeles 2010",
    x = "Population",
    y = NULL
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.y = element_blank(),
    axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
    legend.position = "none"
  ) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = set2_colors) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scientific)

#Second chart: unlabeled, scale in millions, totals outside
plot2 <- ggplot(racial_data, aes(y = race_label, x = population / 1e7, fill = race_label)) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_text(aes(label = scales::comma(population)),
            hjust = ifelse(racial_data$population == "72,828", -0.1, 1.1), 
            color = "black",
            size = 5) +
  labs(
    title = "Population share",
    x = "Population (millions)",
    y = NULL
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.y = element_blank(),
    axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
    legend.position = "none"
  ) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = set2_colors) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = comma)

#Use patchwork to align graphics side by side
plot1 + plot2 + plot_layout(ncol = 2)

# Step 1: Add a total population column
data_2010 <- data_2010 %>%
  mutate(pop_total = pop_white + pop_black + pop_native + pop_asian + pop_other + pop_mixed)
colnames(data_2010)
##  [1] "GISJOIN"    "STATE"      "STATEA"     "COUNTY"     "pop_white" 
##  [6] "pop_black"  "pop_native" "pop_asian"  "pop_other"  "pop_mixed" 
## [11] "pop_total"
# Merge on the GISJOIN key
map_data <- shape_us %>%
  left_join((data_2010), by = "GISJOIN")

# Display the first rows of the pop_total column in map_data
head(map_data$pop_total)
## [1]  54571 182265  27457  22915  57322  10914
# Define the number of population categories
n_classes <- 7
bks <- classInt::classIntervals(c(min(map_data$pop_total) - .00001,
                                  map_data$pop_total),
                                n=n_classes, style = "quantile")$brks
## Warning in classInt::classIntervals(c(min(map_data$pop_total) - 1e-05,
## map_data$pop_total), : var has missing values, omitted in finding classes
# Create categorical population variable based on intervals
map_data  %>% 
  mutate(pop_total_cat = cut(pop_total, bks)) ->
  map_data

levels(map_data$pop_total_cat)

We extracts population data by race for each U.S. county in 2010, cleans it, groups races into categories (White, Black, Native, Asian, Other, Mixed), and we calculates a total population per county. Then, it merges this data with a geographic shapefile of U.S. counties.

Total population is classified into 7 categories based on size and visualized first through a static map using ggplot2.

Task 3: Mapping application into a leaflet application

### Interactive Map with Leaflet

# Safely transform coordinate system to WGS84
map_data_WGS84 <- st_transform(map_data, 4326)

# Create a color palette based on population categories
pal <- leaflet::colorFactor("YlOrRd", domain = map_data_WGS84$pop_total_cat)

# Build the interactive map
leaflet(map_data_WGS84) %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addPolygons(
    fillColor = ~pal(pop_total_cat),
    fillOpacity = 0.8,
    stroke = FALSE,
    popup = ~paste0(
      "<b>County:</b> ", NAME, "<br>",
      "<b>State:</b> ", STATEFP, "<br>",
      "<b>Population:</b> ", format(pop_total, big.mark = ",")
    )
  ) %>%
  addLegend("bottomright", pal = pal, values = ~pop_total_cat,
            title = "Total Population (categories)",
            opacity = 1)

Task 4 : Generating a dynamic dashboard using Shiny

ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel("US county population in 2010"),
  
  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      selectInput("state", "State:", choices = unique(data_2010$STATE), selected = "Alabama"),
      uiOutput("county_ui")
    ),
    
    mainPanel(
      leafletOutput("map", height = 400),
      textOutput("county_id"),
      plotOutput("barplots", height = 400)
    )
  )
)

server <- function(input, output, session) {
  
 # Dynamic county selection by state
  output$county_ui <- renderUI({
    counties <- data_2010 %>%
      filter(STATE == input$state) %>%
      pull(COUNTY) %>% 
      unique() %>% 
      sort()
    
    selectInput("county", "County:", choices = counties)
  })
  
  # Reactive storage for selected county (either via list or map)
  selected_county <- reactiveVal(NULL)
  
  observeEvent(input$map_shape_click, {
    click <- input$map_shape_click
    if (!is.null(click$id)) {
      county_clicked <- map_data_WGS84 %>%
        filter(GISJOIN == click$id) %>%
        pull(COUNTY) %>% unique()
      
      state_clicked <- map_data_WGS84 %>%
        filter(GISJOIN == click$id) %>%
        pull(STATE) %>% unique()
      
      updateSelectInput(session, "state", selected = state_clicked)
      updateSelectInput(session, "county", selected = county_clicked)
    }
  })
  
  
  output$map <- renderLeaflet({
    pal <- colorFactor("YlOrRd", domain = map_data_WGS84$pop_total_cat)
    
    leaflet(map_data_WGS84) %>%
      addTiles() %>%
      addPolygons(
        fillColor = ~pal(pop_total_cat),
        fillOpacity = 0.8,
        stroke = FALSE,
        layerId = ~GISJOIN,  
        popup = ~paste0(
          "<b>County:</b> ", COUNTY, "<br>",
          "<b>State:</b> ", STATE, "<br>",
          "<b>Population:</b> ", format(pop_total, big.mark = ",")
        )
      ) %>%
      addLegend("bottomright", pal = pal, values = ~pop_total_cat,
                title = "Total population (categories)", opacity = 1)
  })
  
  # Barplots for selected county
  output$barplots <- renderPlot({
    req(input$county)
    
    df <- data_2010 %>%
      filter(STATE == input$state, COUNTY == input$county)
    
    racial_data <- df %>%
      summarise(
        pop_white = sum(pop_white, na.rm = TRUE),
        pop_black = sum(pop_black, na.rm = TRUE),
        pop_native = sum(pop_native, na.rm = TRUE),
        pop_asian = sum(pop_asian, na.rm = TRUE),
        pop_other = sum(pop_other, na.rm = TRUE)
      ) %>%
      pivot_longer(cols = everything(), names_to = "race", values_to = "population") %>%
      mutate(
        race_label = recode(race,
                            pop_white = "White",
                            pop_black = "Black",
                            pop_native = "Native",
                            pop_asian = "Asian",
                            pop_other = "Other"),
        race_label = factor(race_label, levels = c("White", "Black", "Asian", "Native", "Other"))
      )
    
    # Couleurs
    set2_colors <- c(
      "White" = "#FF69B4", "Black" = "#556B2F", "Asian" = "#66c2a5",
      "Native" = "#8da0cb", "Other" = "#e78ac3"
    )
    
    # Barplot 1
    plot1 <- ggplot(racial_data, aes(y = race_label, x = population, fill = race_label)) +
      geom_col() +
      geom_text(aes(label = race_label),
                hjust = ifelse(racial_data$race_label == "Native", -0.1, 1.1),
                color = "black", size = 5) +
      labs(title = paste("County:", input$county), x = "Population", y = NULL) +
      theme_minimal() +
      theme(axis.text.y = element_blank(), axis.ticks.y = element_blank(), legend.position = "none") +
      scale_fill_manual(values = set2_colors) +
      scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::scientific)
    
    # Barplot 2
    plot2 <- ggplot(racial_data, aes(y = race_label, x = population / 1e7, fill = race_label)) +
      geom_col() +
      geom_text(aes(label = scales::comma(population)),
                hjust = -0.2, color = "black", size = 5) +
      labs(title = "Population share", x = "Population (millions)", y = NULL) +
      theme_minimal() +
      theme(axis.text.y = element_blank(), axis.ticks.y = element_blank(), legend.position = "none") +
      scale_fill_manual(values = set2_colors) +
      scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::comma)
    
    plot1 + plot2 + plot_layout(ncol = 2)
  })
}

shinyApp(ui, server)
